{
  "doc_id": "37024",
  "text": "For all the experiments described below, male Sprague-Dawley rats (Envigo, Varese, Italy) weighing approximately 220-250 g at the beginning of the experimental procedure, were used. Animals were housed in CeSAL (Centro Stabulazione Animali da Laboratorio, University of Florence) and used at least one week after their arrival. Four rats were housed per cage (size 26 Â 41 cm); animals were fed a standard laboratory diet, tap water ad libitum, and kept at 23 ± 1 C with a 12 h light/dark cycle, light at 7 a.m. [CITATION_1] . All efforts were made to minimize animal suffering and to reduce the number of animals used. Diuretic activity was determined according to the method described by [CITATION_2] and [CITATION_3] , slightly modified. Animals were divided into 4 groups (n ¼ 5) for the acute (single dose) study, with free access to food and water. Before the treatment, all animals received physiological saline (0.9% NaCl) as an oral dose of 2.5 mL/100 g body weight [CITATION_4] to impose a uniform water and salt load, and kept at room temperature. One hour later, rats were treated orally with a dose of 10 mg kg À 1 in the following manner: group I, serving as control, with 0.9% saline; group II with HCT suspension (0.2% p/v HCT in water); groups III, IV and V with selected NLC formulations.",
